From the above matrix we can know that¶

People who spend less time on social media tend to have better mental health, a healthier sleep cycle, fewer relationship conflicts, and lower addiction scores.

Sleep hours and mental health scores are positively correlated, meaning better sleep is associated with better mental health. Both are negatively correlated with social media usage and addiction scores.

Relationship conflicts are positively correlated with social media usage and addiction scores, suggesting that higher usage and addiction are linked to more conflicts.

1. Avg_Daily_Usage_Hours vs. Mental_Health_Score¶

Correlation Coefficients (Negative = Worse Mental Health with More Usage):¶

    High School: -0.84 (Very Strong Negative Correlation)

    Graduate: -0.78 (Strong Negative Correlation)

    Under-Graduate: -0.81 (Very Strong Negative Correlation)

Interpretation:¶

    Across all groups, increased social media usage is strongly linked to poorer mental health.

    The effect is strongest in High School students, possibly due to higher susceptibility to social pressures.

2. Avg_Daily_Usage_Hours vs. Sleep_Hours_Per_Night¶

Correlation Coefficients (Negative = Less Sleep with More Usage):¶

    High School: -0.92 (Extremely Strong Negative Correlation)

    Graduate: -0.73 (Strong Negative Correlation)

    Under-Graduate: -0.84 (Very Strong Negative Correlation)

Interpretation:¶

    Excessive social media use significantly reduces sleep duration, especially in High School students.

    Possible reasons: Late-night scrolling, blue light exposure, or anxiety from social comparisons.

3. Sleep_Hours_Per_Night vs. Mental_Health_Score¶

Correlation Coefficients (Positive = Better Sleep = Better Mental Health):¶

    High School: 0.90 (Very Strong Positive Correlation)

    Graduate: 0.62 (Moderate Positive Correlation)

    Under-Graduate: 0.74 (Strong Positive Correlation)

Interpretation:¶

    Longer sleep hours correlate with better mental health, reinforcing that sleep mediates the negative effects of social media.

    The weaker correlation in Graduate students may suggest other stressors (e.g., work, finances) also impact mental health.

Key Findings Summary¶

    Social media overuse harms mental health and sleep, with the strongest impact on adolescents.

    Sleep deprivation exacerbates mental health issues, creating a vicious cycle.

    Graduate students show slightly weaker correlations, possibly due to greater resilience or different usage patterns (e.g., professional vs. recreational use).

Doing a T test for Undergrades, Grades, and HighSchool to learn the usage pattern¶

In [40]:
from scipy import stats as st
grad_scores = df_cleaned[df_cleaned['Academic_Level'] == 'Graduate']['Addicted_Score']
ugrad_scores = df_cleaned[df_cleaned['Academic_Level'] == 'Undergraduate']['Addicted_Score']

t_stat, p_value = st.ttest_ind(grad_scores, ugrad_scores, equal_var=False)

print("T-statistic:", t_stat)
print("P-value:", p_value)

T-statistic: -2.0831956439212367
P-value: 0.037608641858322356

The p value is less than 0.05 but at 5% level so it is true that udergraduate are more addicted but the - value of T stats says that Grads are comparetively less addicted compared to undergrads¶

In [41]:
high_school = df_cleaned[df_cleaned['Academic_Level']=='High School']['Addicted_Score']
t_stat,p_value=st.ttest_ind(high_school,grad_scores, equal_var=False)
print('T-statstics:', t_stat)
print('P-Value:',p_value)

T-statstics: 7.736290679543667
P-Value: 5.30198916458155e-09

we can see that the p values is way smaller than 0.05 and hence we can confirm the null hypothesis that hgih schoolstudents are more addicted to social media¶

In [42]:
t_stat,p_value=st.ttest_ind(high_school,ugrad_scores, equal_var=False)
print('T-statstics:', t_stat)
print('P-Value:',p_value)

T-statstics: 6.61290381702445
P-Value: 1.215986030508101e-07

As we can see again the Tstat is way higher and the pvalue is still smaller than 0.05 so again we can conclude that the nullhypothesis is true and high school student are more addicted to social media than undergraduates¶

In [46]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder, StandardScaler
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, accuracy_score

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
X=df_cleaned[['Mental_Health_Score','Avg_Daily_Usage_Hours','Sleep_Hours_Per_Night','Addicted_Score','Conflicts_Over_Social_Media']]
X_sc=sc.fit_transform(X)

# determining the K using elbow
winthincSquaredSum=[]
k=10
for i in range(1,k+1):
    kmeans=KMeans(n_clusters=i, init='k-means++', random_state=42, n_init=10)
    kmeans.fit(X_sc)
    winthincSquaredSum.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# plotting the graph

plt.figure(figure=(5,5))
ax=sns.lineplot(x= range(1,k+1), y=winthincSquaredSum, marker='o' , linestyle='--')

In [55]:
df_cleaned_no_outliers = df_cleaned.copy()
column_to_check='Avg_Daily_Usage_Hours'
# Calculate Q1 (25th percentile)
Q1 = df_cleaned_no_outliers[column_to_check].quantile(0.25)
# Calculate Q3 (75th percentile)
Q3 = df_cleaned_no_outliers[column_to_check].quantile(0.75)
# Calculate IQR (Interquartile Range)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

lowerbound=Q1-(1.5*IQR)
outerbound=Q3+(1.5*IQR)
In [56]:

import panel as pn
import pandas as pd
import hvplot.pandas

pn.extension()


# Gender and age filter widgets
gender_options = ['All'] + df_cleaned['Gender'].unique().tolist()
age_options = ['All'] + df_cleaned['Age Group'].unique().tolist()
relationship = ['All']+ df_cleaned['Relationship_Status'].unique().tolist()

gender_select = pn.widgets.Select(name='Select Gender', options=gender_options, value='All')
age_select = pn.widgets.Select(name='Age Group', options=age_options, value='All')
relationship_tag=pn.widgets.Select(name='Relationship Status',options=relationship, value='All')

@pn.depends(selected_gender=gender_select, selected_age=age_select, selected_relationship=relationship_tag)
# Callback function
def update_dashboard(selected_gender, selected_age,selected_relationship ):
    
    # Filtering logic
    filtered_data = df_cleaned.copy()
    
    if selected_gender != 'All':
        filtered_data = filtered_data[filtered_data['Gender'] == selected_gender]
    
    if selected_age != 'All':
        filtered_data = filtered_data[filtered_data['Age Group'] == selected_age]
    if selected_relationship !='All':
        filtered_data=filtered_data[filtered_data['Relationship_Status']==selected_relationship ]
    
    # Display filtered data
    data_table = pn.pane.DataFrame(filtered_data, width=1200, height=200)
    
    # fix platform counts
    platform_counts = (
        filtered_data['Most_Used_Platform']
        .value_counts()
        .reset_index()
    )
    platform_counts.columns = ['Platform', 'Count']
    #platform_counts['Platform'] = platform_counts['Platform'].astype(str)
    platform_counts['Platform'] = platform_counts['Platform'].astype(str)

    bar_plot = platform_counts.hvplot.bar(
        x='Platform',
        y='Count',
        color='skyblue',
        title='Most Used Platform',
        width=1200,
        height=400
    )
    
    return pn.Column(data_table, bar_plot)

# Bind function to widgets
dashboard = pn.bind(update_dashboard, selected_gender=gender_select, selected_age=age_select)

@pn.depends(selected_gender=gender_select, selected_age=age_select, selected_relationship=relationship_tag)
def dashboard2(selected_gender, selected_age,selected_relationship):
     # Filtering logic
    filtered_data = df_cleaned.copy()
    
    if selected_gender != 'All':
        filtered_data = filtered_data[filtered_data['Gender'] == selected_gender]
    
    if selected_age != 'All':
        filtered_data = filtered_data[filtered_data['Age Group'] == selected_age]
    if selected_relationship !='All':
        filtered_data=filtered_data[filtered_data['Relationship_Status']==selected_relationship ]
    
    # Display filtered data
    data_table = pn.pane.DataFrame(filtered_data, width=1200, height=200)

    score_plot = filtered_data.hvplot.box(
        y='Addicted_Score',
        title='Addiction Score Distribution',
        width=500,
        height=400
    )

    # Also show mean addiction score
    mean_score = filtered_data['Addicted_Score'].mean()
    mean_pane = pn.pane.Markdown(f"### Mean Addiction Score: {mean_score:.2f}")

    return pn.Column(mean_pane, score_plot)
